The paper deals with representation learning, which is a key element of state-of-the-art deep learning approaches. It focuses on transforming raw data into structured vector space embeddings, which can capture the distributional semantics of their context. The paper specifically investigates the difference between human perception and context heuristics of basic embedding models, and conducts eye tracking experiments to capture the underlying characteristics of human perception of media documents containing a mixture of text and images. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.CL (Computation and Language) and cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). Additionally, the paper also deals with human-computer interaction and user experience, which suggests the sub-category cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) as another likely option. The paper also proposes a prototypical computational perception-trace model, which involves machine learning techniques, indicating the sub-category cs.LG (Machine Learning) as another possible option. Finally, the paper evaluates the performance of the proposed model on a link-prediction task, which falls under the sub-category cs.IR (Information Retrieval).
